<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-02-17T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-02-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="664" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d664">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">701.9466A/2: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Huddle</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-17T20:00:00-04:00">February
                                    17, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>469. Your 460, February 9, 1 p.m. For Tittmann. It is apparent to us that
                            one of the principal objectives which the Japanese hope to accomplish by
                            the establishment of a mission to the Holy See is to influence Catholic
                            sentiment, particularly in the American Republics and to some extent in
                            China and the Philippines.</p>
                        <p>In your conversations with Vatican officials you may wish to bring this
                            to their attention.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>